  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Grenache from Spain and France?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Spanish Garnacha (Grenache) from regions like Priorat and Campo de Borja tends to be more concentrated and mineral-driven due to slate and clay soils, while French Grenache from Châteauneuf-du-Pape offers more elegance with garrigue herbs and structured tannins from limestone-rich terroir. Spanish versions often show more immediate fruit power and alcohol warmth, whereas French Grenache displays greater complexity and age-worthiness in premium examples.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Grenache a good wine for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, Grenache is excellent for beginners because of its naturally soft tannins, approachable fruit-forward character, and food-friendly nature. The grape's inherent sweetness of fruit (strawberry, cherry, plum) makes it less intimidating than more austere varieties like Cabernet Sauvignon or Nebbiolo. Look for affordable examples from Languedoc or Spanish Campo de Borja to start your Grenache journey without breaking the bank.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I tell if a Grenache wine is high quality?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">High-quality Grenache shows concentrated fruit without jammy sweetness, balanced alcohol (avoid wines over 15.5% ABV), and complex aromatics beyond just red fruit—look for herbs, spice, and mineral notes. The wine should have good structure with present but soft tannins, and premium examples will show terroir expression like the garrigue herbs of southern France or the slate minerality of Priorat. Avoid Grenache that tastes one-dimensional or overly alcoholic, as this indicates poor viticulture or winemaking.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve Grenache wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Grenache at 60-65°F (15-18°C), slightly cooler than room temperature to preserve its fresh fruit character and prevent the alcohol from becoming too prominent. Light, everyday Grenache can be served at the cooler end of this range, while full-bodied examples from Châteauneuf-du-Pape or Priorat benefit from the warmer serving temperature to fully express their complexity. A 15-20 minute chill in the refrigerator before serving is usually perfect.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant Grenache wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young, full-bodied Grenache from premium regions like Châteauneuf-du-Pape or Priorat benefits from 30-60 minutes of decanting to soften tannins and integrate alcohol, while lighter Languedoc or everyday Spanish Garnacha typically doesn't need decanting. Aged Grenache (10+ years) should be decanted carefully to separate from sediment but served shortly after to preserve delicate aromatics. When in doubt, taste first—if the wine seems tight or alcoholic, give it some air time.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Grenache?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is choosing Grenache based solely on high alcohol content, assuming it indicates quality—many over-extracted, jammy examples exceed 16% ABV and lack elegance or food compatibility. Another common error is overlooking single-vineyard Spanish Garnacha in favor of famous French appellations, missing exceptional value wines from regions like Calatayud or Montsant. Always prioritize balance and terroir expression over sheer power when selecting Grenache.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Where can I find the best value Grenache wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Spain's Campo de Borja, Calatayud, and Montsant regions offer exceptional Garnacha values, with old-vine expressions under $20 that rival $40+ French counterparts in quality. In France, look to Languedoc appellations like Minervois and Pic-Saint-Loup rather than prestigious Châteauneuf-du-Pape for affordable quality. Australia's McLaren Vale and Barossa Valley also produce excellent Grenache blends at competitive prices, often showcasing the grape's versatility in warmer climates.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I age premium Grenache wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Top Grenache from Châteauneuf-du-Pape can age 15-25 years, developing complex leather, game, and dried herb notes while maintaining fruit freshness due to the grape's naturally low acidity and high alcohol acting as preservatives. Spanish old-vine Garnacha from Priorat or quality Campo de Borja producers can evolve beautifully for 10-15 years, gaining minerality and spice complexity. However, most everyday Grenache is best consumed within 3-5 years to enjoy its primary fruit character.</p>
  </div>
